Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash and dry all produce.

Peel and grate or mince @garlic{1%clove}. Halve @grape tomatoes{8%ounce}; toss on a #baking sheet{} with half the garlic, a large drizzle of @olive oil{2%teaspoon}, and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Roast on top rack until tomatoes are lightly charred, ~{8-10%minutes}. Transfer to a #medium bowl{}. Carefully wipe off sheet with #paper towels{}.

Meanwhile, pick parsley leaves from @green herb blend{1}(stemmed and minced); mince leaves. Mince chives. In a second medium bowl, combine @ricotta cheese{2}(divided), half the @Parmesan cheese{1/4%cup}(divided, save the rest for serving), and half the minced herbs. Season with salt and a pinch of @chili flakes{1%teaspoon} to taste.

In a #small bowl{}, combine remaining garlic and a large drizzle of @olive oil{2%teaspoon}; season with salt and pepper. Brush one side of each slice of @sourdough bread{4%slices} with garlic oil. Place on baking sheet used for tomatoes. Bake on top rack until toasted, ~{4-5%minutes} total.

Remove sheet from oven; add @walnuts{0.5%ounce} to same sheet. (TIP: If sourdough is done at this point, remove from sheet.) Return to oven until walnuts are toasted, ~{2-3%minutes}. Transfer to a #cutting board{} to cool slightly; roughly chop.

Divide toasts between plates; spread with herby ricotta. Evenly top with tomatoes, walnuts, and remaining Parmesan. Sprinkle with remaining minced herbs and chili flakes to taste. Drizzle with as much @balsamic glaze{5%teaspoon} as you like and serve.